content: Minut, ensi, Morden, pavlini - nice to see you :-)
Dear renju friends, nice to meet you again!
Let me introduce myself first, I am Zhang Jin Yu, from Beijing ,China.
Nice to see you again here Mr. Zhang
I am ill unfortunatelly, but now concetrate on the lesson :-)
The topic of the class is accurate attack and defense. I hope you can find something interesting in the class. I will introduce some games in e-mail tournament.
hi,teacher zhang ,i have been known you a lot
In my understandings of renju, renju technique consists of two things,
one is opening, and the other is calculation in the middle of a game.
I think all of you know the two things but how to do on the two subjects depends on different players.
as I see in Renju, the openings are quite standardized :-)
it is very hard for a player to do extensive and deep research on all the opening,
even in D3 or D11 such popular openings.
The problem is too big and complicated.
Even in e-mail tournament, strong players also will make mistakes in very early stage.
But I know some players did a thorough study when the opponent made an opening. And the win or loss was determined in very early stage.
Someone believe that good opening = huge calculation. Too crazy!
But anyway, do not trust you general opening knowledge when you play in e-mail tournament.
Most of loses in A group comes from opening problems.
I give you some time to read the text above..
you mean sometimes opening is incorrect?
and what's you advise on the opening? I am really puzzled.
let's say not incorrect, but not so preofessional
Now, let us take some simple examples to see it

After 15th it is a general pattern
16th looks not interesting but it is strong!
But it is a lost move
Scm2000 won three players in A group using the pattern with white
this variant has been taught here, so I just use it as an example
won three strongest opponents which led to his champion
This pattern is black sure win first proved by Li Hongbin who is a renju genius
But there were still some players such as Vanalaud, Klimachev using the pattern in 2004 e-mail tournament
could you all follow me? is it fast?
Of course when they made the opening, the fails were destined.
The two examples show that the players must update their opening knowledge quickly
Do not feel too confident that you have known everything in one opening.
But not all the opening mistakes come from the lacking knowledge or the opening trap.
Sometimes your do not have complete study a new pattern but hurry to use it in the game
Now let us see an example. We will analysis the game in detail.
The game comes from e-mail tournament in A group this year.
Klimachev used the same patterns to them.
I think he must be quite confident on the pattern
Klim used similar opening pattern against  several players
So he made the same 11 to two Chinese strong players
but he also worried something and change 11th in Lu's game.
i have no idea, maybe g10
His 13-g8 is the strongest defense as we anticipated
black has been cut to two pieces?
I think it is just his plan. How do you think of that?
i8 and j7 only then white k7?
Some variants are difficult though and without having knowledge about it a player can easily fail the attack in the real game.
